<p><blockquote><b class="sm">Quote:</b><hr size="1" />Hmm, my Rogue is not my main and I don't play him much so may be I am missing something here. You said you want more DPS. Let's look at this. My Rogue will do maximum of 450 or so on backstab with each weapon. With dual wield, I can do 900 maximum, with typical of about 500 or so. With my best weapons, I can do may be 50-60 per weapon for about 120 max or typical of 30 or so.  <br /> <br />So, if I understand what you are saying, you would lose DPS due to not attacking during having the delay and backstab, right? First of all, the delay is 1 second and whatever recycle time for backstabs is, from what I noticed less than 1 second, the total delay is less than 2 seconds. I noticed that even with my best haste, I am losing may be 1-2 rounds of attacks during those 2 seconds. So, 2 rounds x 60 max per weapons x 2 weapons can get me maximum of 240 possible damage. With backstab, I have a chance to do 900. Am I missing something here or is 900 better than 240? <hr size="1" /></blockquote>  <br /> <br />What I think you are missing is that is it not a choice of 900 vs 240, but rather a choice of 900 vs 1140 which is from 900+240. The 1140 is better and the difference adds up over time, just by minimizing the steps betwen attack off and attack on. <br /> <br /> <br /><blockquote><b class="sm">Quote:</b><hr size="1" />I just like to be in sneak mode as much as possible. <hr size="1" /></blockquote> <br /> <br /> <br />This is not a bad idea, especially since the aggro range of wandering mobs is smaller vs a rogue in sneak mode. I personaly do not put it in the macro and just refresh it manually when needed. If a rogue did want to keep it in the macro I would recommend putting it after attack on in that last line of the macro, so as to minimize the attack off time. <br /> <br /> <br /> <br /> <br /><i><span class="sm">Edited, Fri Apr&nbsp;&nbsp;1 15:12:35 2005 by fhrugby</span></i></p>
